com.bluegosling.reflect

Class TypeRef<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bluegosling.reflect.TypeRef<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type represented by this token
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    AnnotatedElement

    public abstract class TypeRef<T>
extends Object
implements AnnotatedElement
    A type token that represents a generic type. Unlike class tokens, which don't adequately support generic classes, this can be used to represent generic types, and it provides access to reifiable generic type information: values for generic type parameters that are known at compile-time. So it can fully represent wildcard types, type variables, and parameterized types.

    This class is effectively a wrapper around the Type interface and provides useful methods to do interesting things related to generic types. In a way, it takes the static utility methods from Types and incorporates them into a type-safe and object-oriented API.

    This class implements AnnotatedElement, but the annotations do not represent annotations on type uses. Rather, they represent annotations on the declared types that a given TypeRef represents (see Types.getAnnotations(Type)). For annotations on type use, you instead want AnnotatedTypeRef.

    • Constructor Detail

      • TypeRef

        protected TypeRef()
        Constructs a new type reference. This is protected so that construction requires the use of a sub-class: 
         TypeRef<List<Map<String, Number>>> type =
   new TypeRef<List<Map<String, Number>>>() { };
        Notice the curly braces, used to construct an anonymous sub-class of TypeRef.

        The generic type must be specified. An exception will be raised otherwise. For example, the following invocation will generated and exception: 

         TypeRef<?> type = new TypeRef() { };
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the generic type parameter is not specified

      • resolveSupertypeRef

        public static <S,T extends S> TypeRef<S> resolveSupertypeRef(TypeRef<T> subtype,
                                                             Class<S> supertype)
        Returns a supertype of the given type, as a TypeRef. This could be an ancestor class of the given type or an interface implemented by the given type.

        This method is similar to resolveSupertypeRef(Class) except that, being a static method, can better express the relationships between the two types and provide a more precise return type.

        Parameters:
        subtype - the type for whom a supertype is queried
        supertype - the supertype
        Returns:
        a TypeRef representation of the specified supertype
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if either of the given types is null
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given supertype is not actually a supertype of the given subtype (which the compiler will only allow when using arguments with raw types)

      • isResolved

        public boolean isResolved()
        Returns true if this type token is resolved, which means that the actual type is known. Resolved types have an underlying type that is a class, a generic array type, or a parameterized type. Other types (wildcard types and type variables) are unresolved. A raw type use of a parameterized type is considered unresolved.
        Returns:
        true if this type token is resolved or false otherwise

      • isFullyResolved

        public boolean isFullyResolved()
        Returns true if this type token is fully resolved, which means that this type is resolved and so are the values for all type arguments (if it is a parameterized type) or for the component type (if it is an array type). A raw type use of a parameterized type is considered unresolved.
        Returns:
        true if this type token is fully resolved or false otherwise

      • asClass

        public Class<T> asClass()
        Returns a Class representation of this type. Unlike using normal class tokens (e.g. MyType.class), this token can encode type arguments. This type can only be represented as a class if it is neither a wildcard nor a type variable.

        This is a convenience for using generic types with APIs that require class tokens: 

         // Won't compile. Generic types are invariant so List != List<String>
 Class<List<String>> clazz = List.class;
 
 // Won't compile. Bad syntax -- can't specify type parameters
 // with a class literal
 Class<List<String>> clazz = List<String>.class;
 
 // TypeRef to the rescue!
 Class<List<String>> clazz =
     new TypeRef<List<String>>() { }.asClass();
        Note that a Class<List<String>> is the same instance as a Class<List<Number>>. Under the hood, they are both List.class. So using the returned class tokens as keys in a map will not work since different class tokens for the same raw type cannot be distinguished. So use caution when, where, and how you use this method.
        Returns:
        a Class
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - if this type is a wildcard or a type variable
        See Also:
        getRawType()

      • getOwnerTypeRef

        public TypeRef<?> getOwnerTypeRef()
        Gets the owner type, as a TypeRef. The owner type is the declaring type of a nested or inner class. Array types will not have an owner type, but their component type might. Wildcard types and type variables also have no owner type, but supertypes representing their upper bounds might. If this type has no owner type then null is returned.
        Returns:
        this type's owner type or null if it has no owner type

      • getSuperclassTypeRef

        public TypeRef<? super T> getSuperclassTypeRef()
        Returns superclass of the current type, as a TypeRef.

        If the super-class is a generic type, its type arguments will be resolved based on the context of the current type. For example, the supertype for a class ListOfSomeType extends ArrayList<SomeType> will be ArrayList<SomeType>, and the resulting type reference will have the type argument E resolved to SomeType.

        Returns:
        the current type's superclass or null if the current type has no superclass (like if it is Object, an interface, a primitive, or void)
        See Also:
        Types.getGenericSuperclass(Type)

      • getInterfaceTypeRefs

        public List<TypeRef<? super T>> getInterfaceTypeRefs()
        Returns the interfaces implemented by the current type, as TypeRefs. This list only includes interfaces directly implemented by this type, not their super-interfaces or interfaces implemented by ancestor classes. The contents and order of the returned list is the same as the contents and order of elements in the array returned by typeRef.getRawType().getInterfaces(). If the current type is an interface then this returns its super-interfaces.

        If any of the interfaces is a generic type, its type arguments will be resolved based on the context of the current type. For example, the interface for a class ListOfSomeType implements List<SomeType> will be List<SomeType>, and the resulting type reference will have the type argument E resolved to SomeType.

        Returns:
        the current type's interfaces or an empty list if the current type does not directly implement any interfaces
        See Also:
        Types.getGenericInterfaces(Type)

      • resolveSupertypeRef

        public TypeRef<? super T> resolveSupertypeRef(Class<?> superclass)
        Returns a supertype of the current type, as a TypeRef. This could be an ancestor class of the current type or an interface implemented by the current type.

        Limitations on the expressiveness of method type variables prevent a more precise return type. Consider instead using the static version, resolveSupertypeRef(TypeRef, Class).

        Parameters:
        superclass - the supertype
        Returns:
        a TypeRef representation of the specified supertype
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the specified type is null
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified type is not actually a supertype of the current type
        See Also:
        Types.resolveSupertype(Type, Class)
